cerally violent dramas, cringeworthy ironic comedies, and trashy reality programs alike, televisual unease trains audiences to survive under late capitalism, which demands that individuals accept a certain amount of discomfort, dread, and irritation into their everyday lives. By highlighting how discomfort has been central to the reorganization and legitimization of television as an art form, Hargraves demonstrates television’s role in assimilating viewers into worlds marked by precarity, perversity, and crisis.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aTelevision broadcastingxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aTelevision programsxInfluencezUnited States. 0aTelevision programszUnited StatesxInfluence. 0aTelevision viewerszUnited States. 0aTelevisionxHistoryy21st centuryzUnited States. 0aTelevisionzUnited StatesxHistoryy21st century. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Television / History & Criticism.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311099775040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478024194?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478024194423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781478024194/original  a978-3-11-099775-0  Duke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles